721521f.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 23rd Street (East)
721521f.text:
Madison Square Park, bounded by Fifth Ave. (foreground) east to Madison
Ave. and East 23rd (right) north to 26th Streets. Prior to 1806 this was
a waste area, and in olden times a burial place for the poor. It was the
site of a U.S. Arsenal, between 1806 to 1823. The first House of Refuge was
founded here in 1825, which burned down in 1839. During the Ma7oralty of
CJames Harper (one of the famous publishers), between 1844 and 1847; this dreary
region was cleared and beautified, and became the famous Madison Square.
To-day this park is surrounded by large buildings, of which the Madison Ave.
contingent predominates; possessing, as it does the Metropolitan Life Insur-
ance Co. Buildings and Tower; the Madison Ave. Building, the Appellate divis-
ion Supreme Court; the 1anhattan Club and the New York Life Insurance Co.
guilding.  The William H. Seward Statue shown in the foreground, (N.E. oor-
ner of Fifth Ave. and East 23rd StrSet), was unveiled in 1876, and is inscrib-
ed: dGowernor, D.S. Senattr, Secretary of State U.S.
1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Writers Project.
